        <person xml:id="amour" sex="M" role="god">
          <persName xml:lang="en">Cupid</persName>
          <persName xml:lang="fr">L'Amour</persName>
          <trait>
            <label>Description:</label>
            <desc>Representational god of love</desc>
            <label>Note of translation:</label>
            <desc>The name used in the original French, <foreign xml:lang="fr">L'Amour</foreign>, is
              ambiguous. Literally, his name means "Love," so he is a personification of the idea,
              but he later appears accompanied "<foreign xml:lang="fr">d'une troupe
                d'Amours</foreign>" 'by a troup of loves,' and they are all armed with darts, or
              arrows. The closest common English approximation to this god of love, then, is Cupid,
              the Roman equivalent of the Greek Eros, more typically known in French as <foreign
                xml:lang="fr">Cupidon</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="fr">Éros</foreign>,
              respectively. Cupid is often loosely interchanged with the Erotes, a plurality of
              Cupidines or "cupids," similarly depicted as winged youths (<rs corresp="#smith-dict"
                >Schmitz, "Eros" 50</rs>). Fuzelier's choice of naming him <foreign xml:lang="fr"
                >L'Amour</foreign> over the equally acceptable <foreign xml:lang="fr"
                >Cupidon</foreign> is a choice that, in the original, narrows the distance between
              the individual and what he represents.</desc>
          </trait>
        </person>

